South African doctor: Omicron is highly contagious but mostly mild
Many doctors and medical experts in South Africa believe that the omicron variant of COVID-19 causes a milder disease than the Delta variant, although it spreads faster.
As the omicron variant spreads in South Africa, a group of more than 5,000 doctors in South Africa's Gauteng province reported that the COVID-19 patients they are currently treating have mild symptoms, such as body pain and coughing, similar to flu, AP reported.
Dr. Unben Pillay, the director of the organization, said he sees dozens of patients every day, but none of them have yet to be hospitalized.
"They are able to control the disease at home, and most people recover within 10 to 14 days of isolation." Pillay said
He said this includes older patients and those with health problems, who are more likely to fall into severe illness from coronavirus infection.
By contrast, he said, in the last wave of Delta, the COVID-19 patients he treated "had difficulty breathing and low blood oxygen levels.
Many people will be hospitalized in a few days".
In the two weeks after the omicron variant was first reported in southern Africa, other doctors shared similar experiences.
While it will take a few weeks to collect enough data, doctors' observations and early evidence provide some clues.
According to South Africa's National Institute of Infectious Diseases, only 30% of COVID-19 patients hospitalized in recent weeks are severe, half the severity of the previous wave; the average length of stay has been reduced from 8 days to 2.8 days; only 3% of recent COVID-19 patients have died, compared to 20% of early outbreaks in South Africa.
Willem Hanekom, director of the African Health Institute, cited data from the National Institute of Infectious Diseases and other reports, saying, "At present, almost all indications are that this is a milder disease."
He added, "It's still early, and we need late data.
Normally, hospitalisations and deaths occur later, and we are only two weeks into this wave. "
At the same time, scientists around the world are looking at case numbers and hospital admissions, while testing the effectiveness of current vaccines and treatments.
While Delta remains the world's leading COVID-19 strain, omicron cases are emerging in dozens of countries, with South Africa at the center of the outbreak.
According to health officials, new cases detected in Gauteng increased by 400% in the first week of December, with tests showing more than 90% of cases of the omicron variant.
Education commentaries: What does it take to save abducted children?
If the analogy is made with the famous public service slogan "no sale, no killing", then, in a good environment without the demand for "trafficking", mass prevention and control, the whole people anti-trafficking, so that trafficking is unprofitable, risky, high cost, such crimes will not occur repeatedly.
Recently, an emergency release platform for missing children developed by the Anti-Trafficking Office of the Criminal Investigation Bureau of the Ministry of Public Security went online.
This is an Internet information platform created for the establishment of an authoritative channel for the release of information on missing children and the timely recovery of abducted children.
Hearing that the App is called "Reunion", I feel warm.
The new technology means not only the name "literature and art", full of feelings, but also the application of information technology is appropriate, practical and effective.
The primary goal of anti-trafficking law enforcement is to recover abducted children and protect their personal safety and freedom.
The second is the trial and punishment of the suspect.
The meaning of criminal punishment, from individual punishment, social prevention to legal education, can be listed in many "big words".
However, priority should be given to the personal safety of the victim before the case of abduction and trafficking is solved.
Prioritizing matters, such as whether the abduction and trafficking of children should be subject to the death penalty or not, can be put aside for careful discussion under the urgent purpose of "seeking help "; however, the matter of rescuing abducted children cannot be discussed.
Based on the experience of investigating such cases, traffickers tend to stay away from the scene of the crime as soon as possible after they are successful.
An extra minute of delay in the search for abductions may make the child one step further away from the parents and make the case more difficult to solve.
In this context, it is indeed practical to come up with effective methods such as the "Reunion" platform that will directly help solve cases and find children.
After all, "anti-trafficking" is a major task that needs to be done by operating the entire legal system.
The fight against crime and the protection of the rights and interests of children and parents, from the improvement of legislation, to the protection of the judiciary, and the meticulous enforcement of law, all need to carry out the care of "protecting the young and supporting the weak".
In addition, the prevention of child abduction and trafficking, from the family to society, can be done better.
For example, in a common case, a family of three is resting at a railway station, and the parents are asleep, only to wake up to find that the child is missing.
A two-year-old cannot be expected to have sufficient self-protection skills, but as a parent of a young child, he or she should have at least a considerable sense of protection.
Taking turns of rest between parents or placing the child under safe protection are the minimum means of preventing child abduction.
From the other side of the police's fight against the crime of abduction and trafficking, the side that buys abducted children should also be concerned and punished.
A single wrongful act is often just one link in a long chain.
According to the Criminal Law of China, the legal penalty for the crime of child abduction and trafficking is five years; in particularly serious cases, the death penalty can be imposed and property confiscated.
The starting point is high and the maximum penalty is heavy, and under the general trend of "light punishment", the crime of child abduction and trafficking is clearly a crime with a heavier penalty.
But there are still a lot of cases of abduction and trafficking every year.
It can be seen that some people are backward in their concept of raising children, and their legal awareness is weak.
Legal education for this group of people should be followed up simultaneously.
In order to effectively control the crime of abduction and trafficking, strict law enforcement by the authorities alone cannot be relied on.
If the "market" for trafficking is widespread, and the traffickers are motivated by profit, constantly innovate the means of trafficking, and form a "law-fighting" situation with the law-enforcers, the anti-trafficking operation will inevitably fall into a quagmire of inefficiency.
Therefore, the elimination of backward concepts and the popularization of common sense in the law will also help to eradicate the crime of abduction, trafficking and purchase of children.
