Biden says freedom never goes out as democracy summit ends
The online "Summit for Democracy" convened by US President Joe Biden and attended by governments, civil society and private sector leaders from 110 countries around the world concluded on Friday (December 10).
Biden said in his closing remarks that the fire of freedom burns in the hearts of everyone in the world, and that authoritarian regimes can never extinguish it.
He also said he planned to hold a second global "democracy summit" next year.
Taiwan government representative and councillor Tang Feng and Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Law Guanchong, currently in exile in the UK, also spoke at the summit on the second day.
Biden said, "We know how difficult the job ahead of us is.
But we also know that we can meet the challenge, because as I said before, as this summit has shown, the democratic world is everywhere.
Authoritarian regimes can never extinguish the small fire of freedom, which burns in the hearts of people all over the world and all over the world. "
Biden also said defending democracy requires the concerted efforts of society as a whole.
"As leaders of government, we have a responsibility to listen to our citizens, strengthen the guardrails of democracy, push for reform, achieve transparent and accountable governance, and be more resilient to the buffer and shock forces of autocracy, and those who want to pursue power naked before the public interest.", he said
On the second day of the "Democracy Summit", the themes were defending human rights, consolidating democracy and confronting authoritarianism, and countering digital authoritarianism and affirming democratic values.
This day coincides with International Human Rights Day.
In his opening remarks on the day, UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres also said that the cause of democracy faces challenges around the world, especially those brought about by emerging digital technologies.
"It is time to reaffirm common values and positions and democratic resilience," he said.
This requires deepening social dialogue, addressing inequality, fighting corruption, renewing the social contract, investing in quality education, and expanding opportunities for women and girls.
It also requires a firm condemnation of all forms of populism, nativism, and extremism, including the use of all the tools offered by the technological revolution. "
Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Law Guanchong addressed the summit through a pre-recorded video, reminding participants to continue to pay attention to the human rights situation in Hong Kong and among Chinese ethnic minorities such as the Uyghur and Tibetan minorities.
"For a long time, the world has accepted China's rise without establishing a mechanism to hold it accountable," he said.
That is why politicians and civil society leaders must work together.
We have to use all [resources] we have to ensure that the revival of democracy is our top priority. "
Law also called for the free world to unite against the threat of the CCP.
"Maybe some of you are afraid to annoy General Secretary Xi Jinping, maybe some of you don't want to lose the Chinese market, maybe some of you don't realize the threat to our democratic values," he said.
And that's why we failed.
That's why we have to change. "
During a round-table discussion on "Combating Digital Dictatorship and Affirming Democratic Values," Tang Feng, a member of Taiwan's Executive Yuan, released a "National Statement" via video, stressing that Taiwan is at the forefront of the fight against despotism and authoritarianism.
He also shared his experience in fighting COVID-19 through transparency and building trust.
"As Taiwan's democracy is in the ascendant, we have always been firmly at the forefront of the global fight against authoritarianism, and have played a leading role in promoting global freedom, democracy, and human rights," he said.
During the epidemic, authoritarian governments everywhere justified human rights abuses in the name of public health and collective interests, and global democracy showed signs of regression.
But in Taiwan, we don't have to shut down the city to control the epidemic, and we don't have to remove the shelf to defeat disinformation. "
As the second day of the "Democracy Summit" was scheduled, the US Treasury Department announced sanctions against 15 individuals and 10 entities in several countries, including China and North Korea, who were found to have committed serious human rights abuses, and investment restrictions on a Chinese company found to have used surveillance technology to assist in human rights abuses.
