Vietnam People's Daily-Gulf Cooperation Council meets common challenges
Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman's stops include Oman, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Bahrain and Kuwait.
Notably, it was Crown Prince Mohammed's first visit to Qatar since Saudi Arabia and its Arab allies imposed an embargo on Qatar in mid-2017, leading to a diplomatic crisis in the Gulf.
During the crisis, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain and Egypt severed diplomatic relations with Qatar and imposed a comprehensive embargo on it, accusing it of supporting terrorist groups and having close ties with Iran.
Diplomatic tensions have seriously affected the internal cohesion of the GCC and have had a negative impact on the economies of countries in the region.
Four Arab countries have blocked land, sea and air routes leading to Qatar.
The crisis was resolved only at the Gulf Cooperation Council summit in January 2021, when the Gulf countries signed an agreement mediated by the United States and Kuwait towards "unity and stability".
Saudi Arabia has reopened its border with Qatar.
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are leading efforts to restore relations with Qatar through the appointment of new ambassadors by both countries in Qatar.
The resolution of differences among the Gulf Arab countries in order to restore relations with Qatar stems from the need to unite for the benefit of all countries and regional stability, and is aimed at addressing common challenges.
During the Saudi crown prince's visit to Oman, the two sides agreed to open the first direct land corridor between the two Gulf neighbors.
The 725-kilometer corridor connecting the two countries will facilitate the travel of citizens of both countries and the integration of supply chains.
Saudi Arabia's Public Investment Fund (PIF) will invest $5 billion in Oman, and companies from the two countries have signed 13 memorandums of understanding worth $30 billion.
The Saudi crown prince's visit to the Gulf states coincided with negotiations between Iran and world powers to salvage the Iran nuclear deal called the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA) -an agreement condemned by the Gulf Arab states for believing it would not resolve the missile issue with Iran.
The Gulf states have long regarded Iran as a "competitor" and as a "threat" to regional security.
The Gulf states believe that it is flawed not to resolve the Iranian missile issue and not to take action to curb Iranian activities in the region.
Saudi Arabia has engaged in direct negotiations with Iran against the backdrop of nuclear negotiations between the major powers and Iran that failed to meet the aspirations of the Gulf states.
Its goal is to contain the escalation of tensions in the region.
This is one of the factors slowing economic growth in the GCC countries.
The upcoming GCC summit will be the first among GCC countries since the dispute between some member states and Qatar ended.
This is an opportunity for the GCC to reassess the diplomatic achievements that have contributed to the restoration of GCC unity, while proposing measures to enable its member States to fully cooperate in addressing common challenges and contributing to the stability and development of the Gulf States.
