Asian-American groups complain about discrimination in admissions at 3 Ivy League schools, including Yale - Xinhuanet
WASHINGTON, May 23 (Xinhua) --More than 130 Asian-American groups filed a complaint with the U.S. Department of Education and Department of Justice on Wednesday to protest against discrimination against Asian-American applicants at three Ivy League schools--Yale University, Brown University, and Dartmouth College.
The Asian Education Alliance, which led the complaint, held a press conference in Washington on the same day.
In the past 10 years, the number of Asian applicants eligible for admission to prestigious U.S. schools has doubled, but the proportion of Asian applicants among the three prestigious U.S. schools has remained at the same level, Zhao Yukong, chairman of the group, said at the press conference.
Many studies have shown that these universities "consistently and systematically discriminate against Asian applicants" in the so-called "comprehensive" admissions process.
Zhao said that a 2014 study by Sanders and other scholars showed that among the three universities, Asian Americans had the lowest admission rate of any ethnic group relative to the number of applicants.
Data from the U.S. Department of Education also shows that of all Ivy League schools, Brown University and Dartmouth College have the lowest admission rates for Asian students, and Yale University and Brown University have implemented de facto racial quotas for Asian applicants for more than 20 years.
Zhao told Xinhua that they expected the U.S. Department of Education and Department of Justice to investigate the complaint and take measures to stop the universities from continuing to discriminate against Asian Americans in their admissions if they found the facts.
They also expect the universities complained of to take the initiative to pay attention to the issue and change their admissions policies for Asian Americans.
At present, the three universities complained of have not responded.
The Asian Education Alliance was founded in 2015, when it complained about discrimination in admissions to Harvard University, but the U.S. Department of Education did not accept it on procedural grounds.
In addition to Chinese-American groups, educational groups of Indian, Korean, Japanese, and Pakistani descent in the United States also participated in the complaint.
